💵 Not every haircut is supposed to be a fade, taper, edge-up or design. Quite a few of my top paying clients don’t want or require any of the mentioned styles. Sometimes the high end clients prefer a tasteful look that looks more lived in or balanced. Most barbers I see over look these cuts because a.) they think they are “easy” or b.) do not like the style because they may think it doesn’t demonstrate their “skills” as a barber.

But, I would argue that it is more of a flex by being able to successfully accommodate both properly! #Iykyk #gentlemenshaircut #mensfashion #menshair #menstrim #howtostylemenshair #blowdry #shearwork #thebestpaste #menshairworld

I’ve been going through some internal issues as of the passed couple years. With out going into detail I wanted to share…

I just want to be transparent and let ya’ll know even your favorite Influencer/Barber, whatever struggles…hard. I know it’s not “cool” to show it bc that would smell like weakness. Specifically on social media but I figured I’d share a little bit…

I want you to know that mental health is real. Especially with today’s men…and I want you to know that it’s ok and normal to feel down, insecure, depressed, like a failure, like a mistake, like less than, etc…

I feel as though dark clouds loom over my head most days but I cling to the brightest light in my life, my family. 

I will leave you with a piece of advice that has really helped me a lot…when your moments feel heavy, look for something to be grateful for. Start with the silliest little thing if you have to and build from there. 

It doesn’t make anything go away but it does allow you to keep one foot in front of the other. Even if that’s all you’ve got. 

📸: @angelricci35 

#mensmentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness

Maybe it’s the punk rock in me but man oh man am I tired of barbers acting like they are the authority on everything barber related.

Everybody’s way is bias! 

I’ve owned the shop, I’ve been on commision, I’ve been the renter, I’ve been in a suite, I’ve done house calls, I’ve cut out the basement, I’ve cut in 90+ degrees, I’ve cut in the dark…blah blah blah blah.

All that might be MY experience but if there is one thing I have learned (especially since the pandemic) is that EVERYONE has a different path.

One person’s business/hustle might look different than another.

This causes frustration and confusion. 

When I give advice, just know I am not saying my way is “The Way”. Because, it’s not. 

Want to know why this simply can’t be true? 

Because times change. The passed couple years I have seen hair base business’ open and then close, come and then go. 

The world is changing. It’s what it does.

Imagine if we were telling barbers to do the same thing we did in 2005? 

“Just have your clients wait against the wall all day until it’s their turn!” 

Yea, that’s 2005 but look, it’s 2023!!

So how can we pretend we have the answers for everyone? 

Let yourself evolve for what works for you and YOUR brand. 

-M.R.K. 

#business #entrepreneur #barbertalk #howtocuthair #howtobeabarber #idgaf

Finally got my lazy ass to open up the @_nicolerenae (congrats again home girl, you a savage!) Baby Blue Lo Pro’s…I vary familiar with @babylisspro_barberology tools but I do like what they did with the lever on the clipper. Opens all the way up to a number 1. Yea, so I didn’t even need my 1.5 guard AT ALL. Which means, speed accuracy and all in one. I like it a lot. The DLC 2.0 blade always slaps on the T outliner so no problems there.

My only slight concern with the clipper was the performance in the zero to skin area. That part did take some extra time to knock out.

All in all - 4.5/5. Nasty Combo for an entire haircut. 🔥

This is my homie @peepthemic He is my partner in the barber studio. I just found out he is leaving for Dallas. As all good things, it must come to an end (soon). 

But, what can I say about him…I love the guy. He is young but he has an understanding about him that is rare. He has passion, humility and perseverance. He is independent and a non bullshitter (like myself, probably why we get along so well), and he likes to learn about hair AND more importantly- LIFE. 

But I think what I love about him the most is that he is kind…he is considerate…and today that’s super rare. 

Anyway, I did this haircut on him a couple days ago but his hair grows like a chia pet so by the time I post this, he’ll probably need another cut.

Safe travels to Dallas my bro. And remember whenever you feel nervous, frustrated or unsure, look back at this post and remember that you are a beast and have ALL the tools to get what you want out of life!!!

Whelp. My brother came is with an undercut comb over. It’s not 2010 though…so I had restart him. What ya think?

I think the thing that barbers forget is that the haircutting business is primarily a 1099 or self employed business. I have been seeing all the BS about barbers not charging enough and other barbers charging too much. 20 min cuts or 1 hr??? To be honest, from my perspective? I think this is all because everybody is comparing themselves to others through a skewed lenses…

First of all, I miss the days when barbers use to admire each others craft and not their pockets…(btw, that’s very telling of what’s going on in the industry & economy).

Secondly, as a self employed barber I have the RIGHT to charge whatever I want. I have the RIGHT to cut hair in 15 mins or an hr and a half. I have the right to cut 1 head a day or 14. IT DOES NOT MATTER.

Thirdly, don’t let social media make you feel less than or more than based off what you SEE on this cell phone screen…I promise you that the best thing you can do is to analyze your business based off of how happy you are in it. If you don’t like something, change it. Try new sh*t. 

This haircutting thing is not rocket science I promise. 

-M.R.K. 

#howtobeabarber #howtofade #barbertalk #haircuttingeducation 

@andrewdoeshair @beauty_fades @absolutebarbersupply @arlyssaa @barberphil15 @delastoryofficial @peepthemic @o_g_walker @g.uss @titan_barber @kixpo @_barber_q

You might laugh but my first legit job as a barber here in El Paso, Texas was on Fort Bliss. I had a flow-bee (vacuum) attached to my clipper and I was told to knock out haircuts as quick as I could. Of course haircuts on post were only $5.95 at the time, and I was on 50% commission (yes, I said 50%!). 

One day I hit a record for 22 haircuts in a short 4 hour shift.

NOT BRAGGING!

My point is, after learning speed & “efficiency” I also learned that these haircuts were not enjoyable for the client or myself. It was 100% about meeting a necessity. And it felt wrong. I felt wrong. I wanted to be wanted. Not a necessary haircut machine. 

So, I started experimenting with paying attention to how my clients felt about their hair and if I asked the right questions, some would even start requesting small but specific things.

Maybe it was a line up in the front instead of natural. Maybe it was a lower fade than the standard high and tight. 

Little things like that started taking a couple more minutes than normal, but guess what? These military clients started tipping me 5-10, some times 15 dollars more for the extra couple mins I took to pay more attention. Of course the manager of the shop did not like that at all. She never forgot to remind me, “Michael, you are taking way too long on these haircuts. You’re not going to make any money!”

Little did she know my tips were making me plenty more than probably most of the barbers on post AND most importantly, I WAS HAPPIER.

That’s what I call a win-win. 

My point is, it’s not wrong or less than to be a haircut machine. Speed & efficiency has it’s place in the world but so does everything else. I wouldn’t be who I am today with out learning that type of grind because it gives me perspective and it’s a skill I can always call on when needed but what I learned is who I wanted to be. I wanted to be a barber who was desired for his vision, service and art…and some times when THAT is your priority, speed & efficiency isn’t at the forefront of your mind, the final outcome is.

-M.R.K. 

#howtobeabarber #howtofade #menshaircut #militaryhaircut #menshair
Hey look a fade.
I still “work”.

Today is my birthday. What can I pass on to you? What have I learned?
Well, not much lol. The older I get the more I realize that there is a TON
I do not and will not ever know. 

And that’s ok because there are 3 things I do know and I think you
could benefit from them as well:

1- Find a way to love yourself. Treat yourself with grace. Be patient with 
your progress. Take the time to learn how to be 100% present with your
self and who you are. 

2- Do what you love. I was lucky I found barbering early in life…but I also
found out through the years that I love new & old experiences. I love
skateboarding, sports, travel & simple things- like a nice cup of coffee. 

3- Lastly, find someone to love. Wether that’s your parents, friends, or
creating a family of your own. Learning to love others as yourself is
a universal truth that EVERYONE needs to exercise. Love makes you a
better human and connects you to the big picture and keeps a healthy
perspective. 

Hopefully this helps you and keeps you centered as it does me. 

Also, a big thanks to all those who support in anyway possible!

📸: @angelricci35 

#libraseason #happybirthday #oldmanvibes
